{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01X7pYWdh94r2K57ACWKrJRs","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 24 Failure Analysis\n     2→\n     3→All 18 failures are on generated files. No real-file failures.\n     4→\n     5→---\n     6→\n     7→## Pattern 1: OCR digit-for-letter in title — partial correction (4 failures)\n     8→\n     9→**Cases:** Beet Arugula Salad, Blackberry Fool, Chleb Pszenny Razowy, Lemon Herb Grilled Chicken\n    10→\n    11→**What happened:** The title was correctly identified as the first line, but OCR artifacts\n    12→(1→l/i, Í→I) were not fully normalized. The extractor returned the title with residual\n    13→corruption rather than the clean form.\n    14→\n    15→```\n    16→\"BEET ARUGU1A SA1AD\"  →  \"Beet Aruguia Saiad\"   (expected: Beet Arugula Salad)\n    17→\"B1ACKBERRY FOO1\"    →  \"Biackberry Fooi\"        (expected: Blackberry Fool)\n    18→\"CH1EB PSZENNY RAZOWY\" → \"Chieb Pszenny Razowy\"  (expected: Chleb Pszenny Razowy)\n    19→\"LEMON HERB GRILÍED CHICKEN\" → \"Lemon Herb Grilied Chicken\"\n    20→```\n    21→\n    22→**Why:** The extractor is doing some normalization (e.g. lowercasing, stripping formatting)\n    23→but not applying consistent digit-to-letter substitution rules. `1` is sometimes converted\n    24→to `l` and sometimes to `i`, with no semantic check.\n    25→\n    26→---\n    27→\n    28→## Pattern 2: OCR corruption annotation confuses extractor (5 failures)\n    29→\n    30→**Cases:** Braised Cod with White Wine, Drożdże Sernik, Piernik z Śliwkami, Roasted Beet\n    31→and Walnut Dip, Żurek Krakowski\n    32→\n    33→**What happened:** The title IS the first line, but it's followed immediately by an\n    34→`(OCR CORRUPTION: ...)` annotation on line 3 and `lngredients:` (l for I) on line 5.\n    35→The extractor either returned empty or skipped to a random body line:\n    36→\n    37→```\n    38→\"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\"  →  \"\"  (empty)\n    39→\"Drożdże Sern1k\"               →  \"Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.\"  (serving instruction)\n    40→\"P1ern1k z Śliwkami\"           →  \"Podaw4ć ciepło ze śmietaną lub lodami.\"\n    41→\"Roasted Beet and Walnut D1p\"  →  \"\"  (empty)\n    42→\"Żurek Krakowski\"              →  \"XxYyZz salt and pepper\"\n    43→```\n    44→\n    45→**Why:** The `(OCR CORRUPTION: ...)` annotation and the garbage tokens throughout the body\n    46→(e.g. `XxYyZz`, `Podaw4ć`) are being misread — the extractor apparently discards the first\n    47→line as too corrupted (it contains digits), then fails to find a clean candidate, and\n    48→either returns empty or picks the first \"sentence-like\" string from the body.\n    49→\n    50→---\n    51→\n    52→## Pattern 3: Category/section header precedes the actual title (3 failures)\n    53→\n    54→**Cases:** Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce, Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan, Ogórkowa Zupa\n    55→\n    56→**What happened:** A non-title line appears before the recipe title — either a book-section\n    57→label (`FISH & SEAFOOD`, `VEGETABLES`) or a metadata bar (`Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | ...`).\n    58→The extractor misidentifies what follows as description, not title:\n    59→\n    60→```\n    61→\"FISH & SEAFOOD\" / \"Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce\" → \"In same pan, sauté shallots...\"\n    62→\"VEGETABLES\" / \"Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan\"      → \"Simple yet elegant vegetable dish...\"\n    63→\"Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | ...\" / \"OGÓRKOWA ZUPA\"   → \"\"\n    64→```\n    65→\n    66→**Why:** The extractor treats the first prominent all-caps or pipe-delimited line as the\n    67→title, pushing the actual title into a \"description\" position that it then skips, ultimately\n    68→falling through to a body sentence or returning empty.\n    69→\n    70→---\n    71→\n    72→## Pattern 4: Title absent from the beginning of captured text (2 failures)\n    73→\n    74→**Cases:** Mushroom Risotto, Sweet Potato Salad\n    75→\n    76→**What happened:** The OCR capture starts mid-recipe — either mid-instruction or straight\n    77→at the ingredient list — so there is no title present at all:\n    78→\n    79→```\n    80→Mushroom Risotto: starts with \"Reduce heat and stir in the remaining stock...\"\n    81→  → extracted \"CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA + CARPACCIO WITH CITRUS DRESSING\"\n    82→     (title of the NEXT recipe in the same file)\n    83→\n    84→Sweet Potato Salad: starts with \"2 large sweet potatoes, peeled and cut...\"\n    85→  → extracted \"Salt and pepper\"\n    86→```\n    87→\n    88→**Why:** With no title available on the page, the extractor either picks up a later recipe's\n    89→title (the file contains multiple recipes) or grabs the first short phrase that looks\n    90→title-like.\n    91→\n    92→---\n    93→\n    94→## Pattern 5: Compound title with variation notation — only variation extracted (2 failures)\n    95→\n    96→**Cases:** HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION),\n    97→PIERNIK TRADYCYJNY + PIERNIK NOWOCZESNY Z CZEKOLADĄ\n    98→\n    99→**What happened:** The full compound title is on line 1, but the extractor discards it in\n   100→favor of an internal section header from later in the file:\n   101→\n   102→```\n   103→\"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION)\"\n   104→  → \"--VARIATION: PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS\"\n   105→\n   106→\"PIERNIK TRADYCYJNY + PIERNIK NOWOCZESNY Z CZEKOLADĄ\"\n   107→  → \"--WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ\"\n   108→```\n   109→\n   110→**Why:** The `:` and `+` separators in these titles may be triggering split logic that\n   111→treats only one segment as the title. The `--` prefix in the output suggests the extractor\n   112→is recognizing these as variation markers and outputting only the variation name.\n   113→\n   114→---\n   115→\n   116→## Pattern 6: Polish title + English subtitle on line 2 (1 failure)\n   117→\n   118→**Cases:** Golonka\n   119→\n   120→**What happened:** The first line is the Polish name, the second line is an English\n   121→translation/subtitle. The extractor skips both and returns an instruction sentence:\n   122→\n   123→```\n   124→\"Golonka\" / \"Roasted Pork Knuckle\"\n   125→  → \"Scatter vegetables around pan. + Sauce: Remove knuckles and vegetables from pan. ...\"\n   126→```\n   127→\n   128→**Why:** The extractor apparently sees \"Golonka\" as too short or ambiguous, treats the\n   129→English line as a subtitle (not a title), and then falls through to body content. The `+`\n   130→separator in the output suggests the instruction-concatenation path was triggered.\n   131→\n   132→---\n   133→\n   134→## Pattern 7: Heavy OCR corruption in body with title on first line (1 failure)\n   135→\n   136→**Cases:** Placki Ziemniaczane\n   137→\n   138→**What happened:** The title `PLACKI ZIEMNIACZANE` is cleanly on line 1, but the body is\n   139→extremely corrupted (`SKLADNIK1`, `d0 miałkuchu siatek`, `Sp|aszcz paіką`). The extractor\n   140→returned a corrupted body instruction instead:\n   141→\n   142→```\n   143→\"PLACKI ZIEMNIACZANE\"  →  \"Sp|aszcz paіką do grubość-ci około 1 centyme-tra.\"\n   144→```\n   145→\n   146→**Why:** Similar to Pattern 2 — pervasive corruption in the body may cause the extractor\n   147→to distrust even the clean first line and scan further, landing on a body sentence.\n   148→\n   149→---\n   150→\n   151→## Summary by impact\n   152→\n   153→| Pattern | Count | Affects real files? |\n   154→|---------|-------|---------------------|\n   155→| 1. OCR digits in title, partial correction | 4 | Possible — real scans can have digit/letter OCR errors |\n   156→| 2. OCR corruption annotation confuses extractor | 5 | No — annotation is synthetic test scaffolding |\n   157→| 3. Category/section header before title | 3 | Yes — cookbook pages often have chapter headers |\n   158→| 4. No title in captured text | 2 | Yes — page crops can miss the title |\n   159→| 5. Compound title with `:` / `+` variation | 2 | Yes — multi-recipe pages exist in real data |\n   160→| 6. Subtitle on line 2 | 1 | Yes — bilingual titles appear in real cookbook scans |\n   161→| 7. Heavy body corruption, clean title skipped | 1 | Possible — bad scan quality in real files |\n   162→\n   163→The highest-priority fixes for real-file robustness are Patterns 3, 4, and 5.\n   164→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ae7c1124-3c84-467a-af52-dc284b447f62","uuid":"d9686057-3d41-468e-b8d6-bdd529aee4d4","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/24-b15aa30/feedback.md","content":"# Iteration 24 Failure Analysis\n\nAll 18 failures are on generated files. No real-file failures.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 1: OCR digit-for-letter in title — partial correction (4 failures)\n\n**Cases:** Beet Arugula Salad, Blackberry Fool, Chleb Pszenny Razowy, Lemon Herb Grilled Chicken\n\n**What happened:** The title was correctly identified as the first line, but OCR artifacts\n(1→l/i, Í→I) were not fully normalized. The extractor returned the title with residual\ncorruption rather than the clean form.\n\n```\n\"BEET ARUGU1A SA1AD\"  →  \"Beet Aruguia Saiad\"   (expected: Beet Arugula Salad)\n\"B1ACKBERRY FOO1\"    →  \"Biackberry Fooi\"        (expected: Blackberry Fool)\n\"CH1EB PSZENNY RAZOWY\" → \"Chieb Pszenny Razowy\"  (expected: Chleb Pszenny Razowy)\n\"LEMON HERB GRILÍED CHICKEN\" → \"Lemon Herb Grilied Chicken\"\n```\n\n**Why:** The extractor is doing some normalization (e.g. lowercasing, stripping formatting)\nbut not applying consistent digit-to-letter substitution rules. `1` is sometimes converted\nto `l` and sometimes to `i`, with no semantic check.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 2: OCR corruption annotation confuses extractor (5 failures)\n\n**Cases:** Braised Cod with White Wine, Drożdże Sernik, Piernik z Śliwkami, Roasted Beet\nand Walnut Dip, Żurek Krakowski\n\n**What happened:** The title IS the first line, but it's followed immediately by an\n`(OCR CORRUPTION: ...)` annotation on line 3 and `lngredients:` (l for I) on line 5.\nThe extractor either returned empty or skipped to a random body line:\n\n```\n\"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\"  →  \"\"  (empty)\n\"Drożdże Sern1k\"               →  \"Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.\"  (serving instruction)\n\"P1ern1k z Śliwkami\"           →  \"Podaw4ć ciepło ze śmietaną lub lodami.\"\n\"Roasted Beet and Walnut D1p\"  →  \"\"  (empty)\n\"Żurek Krakowski\"              →  \"XxYyZz salt and pepper\"\n```\n\n**Why:** The `(OCR CORRUPTION: ...)` annotation and the garbage tokens throughout the body\n(e.g. `XxYyZz`, `Podaw4ć`) are being misread — the extractor apparently discards the first\nline as too corrupted (it contains digits), then fails to find a clean candidate, and\neither returns empty or picks the first \"sentence-like\" string from the body.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 3: Category/section header precedes the actual title (3 failures)\n\n**Cases:** Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce, Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan, Ogórkowa Zupa\n\n**What happened:** A non-title line appears before the recipe title — either a book-section\nlabel (`FISH & SEAFOOD`, `VEGETABLES`) or a metadata bar (`Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | ...`).\nThe extractor misidentifies what follows as description, not title:\n\n```\n\"FISH & SEAFOOD\" / \"Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce\" → \"In same pan, sauté shallots...\"\n\"VEGETABLES\" / \"Roasted Asparagus with Parmesan\"      → \"Simple yet elegant vegetable dish...\"\n\"Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB | ...\" / \"OGÓRKOWA ZUPA\"   → \"\"\n```\n\n**Why:** The extractor treats the first prominent all-caps or pipe-delimited line as the\ntitle, pushing the actual title into a \"description\" position that it then skips, ultimately\nfalling through to a body sentence or returning empty.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 4: Title absent from the beginning of captured text (2 failures)\n\n**Cases:** Mushroom Risotto, Sweet Potato Salad\n\n**What happened:** The OCR capture starts mid-recipe — either mid-instruction or straight\nat the ingredient list — so there is no title present at all:\n\n```\nMushroom Risotto: starts with \"Reduce heat and stir in the remaining stock...\"\n  → extracted \"CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA + CARPACCIO WITH CITRUS DRESSING\"\n     (title of the NEXT recipe in the same file)\n\nSweet Potato Salad: starts with \"2 large sweet potatoes, peeled and cut...\"\n  → extracted \"Salt and pepper\"\n```\n\n**Why:** With no title available on the page, the extractor either picks up a later recipe's\ntitle (the file contains multiple recipes) or grabs the first short phrase that looks\ntitle-like.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 5: Compound title with variation notation — only variation extracted (2 failures)\n\n**Cases:** HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION),\nPIERNIK TRADYCYJNY + PIERNIK NOWOCZESNY Z CZEKOLADĄ\n\n**What happened:** The full compound title is on line 1, but the extractor discards it in\nfavor of an internal section header from later in the file:\n\n```\n\"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION)\"\n  → \"--VARIATION: PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS\"\n\n\"PIERNIK TRADYCYJNY + PIERNIK NOWOCZESNY Z CZEKOLADĄ\"\n  → \"--WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ\"\n```\n\n**Why:** The `:` and `+` separators in these titles may be triggering split logic that\ntreats only one segment as the title. The `--` prefix in the output suggests the extractor\nis recognizing these as variation markers and outputting only the variation name.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 6: Polish title + English subtitle on line 2 (1 failure)\n\n**Cases:** Golonka\n\n**What happened:** The first line is the Polish name, the second line is an English\ntranslation/subtitle. The extractor skips both and returns an instruction sentence:\n\n```\n\"Golonka\" / \"Roasted Pork Knuckle\"\n  → \"Scatter vegetables around pan. + Sauce: Remove knuckles and vegetables from pan. ...\"\n```\n\n**Why:** The extractor apparently sees \"Golonka\" as too short or ambiguous, treats the\nEnglish line as a subtitle (not a title), and then falls through to body content. The `+`\nseparator in the output suggests the instruction-concatenation path was triggered.\n\n---\n\n## Pattern 7: Heavy OCR corruption in body with title on first line (1 failure)\n\n**Cases:** Placki Ziemniaczane\n\n**What happened:** The title `PLACKI ZIEMNIACZANE` is cleanly on line 1, but the body is\nextremely corrupted (`SKLADNIK1`, `d0 miałkuchu siatek`, `Sp|aszcz paіką`). The extractor\nreturned a corrupted body instruction instead:\n\n```\n\"PLACKI ZIEMNIACZANE\"  →  \"Sp|aszcz paіką do grubość-ci około 1 centyme-tra.\"\n```\n\n**Why:** Similar to Pattern 2 — pervasive corruption in the body may cause the extractor\nto distrust even the clean first line and scan further, landing on a body sentence.\n\n---\n\n## Summary by impact\n\n| Pattern | Count | Affects real files? |\n|---------|-------|---------------------|\n| 1. OCR digits in title, partial correction | 4 | Possible — real scans can have digit/letter OCR errors |\n| 2. OCR corruption annotation confuses extractor | 5 | No — annotation is synthetic test scaffolding |\n| 3. Category/section header before title | 3 | Yes — cookbook pages often have chapter headers |\n| 4. No title in captured text | 2 | Yes — page crops can miss the title |\n| 5. Compound title with `:` / `+` variation | 2 | Yes — multi-recipe pages exist in real data |\n| 6. Subtitle on line 2 | 1 | Yes — bilingual titles appear in real cookbook scans |\n| 7. Heavy body corruption, clean title skipped | 1 | Possible — bad scan quality in real files |\n\nThe highest-priority fixes for real-file robustness are Patterns 3, 4, and 5.\n","numLines":164,"startLine":1,"totalLines":164}}}
