{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SGKrcej5Cqv2h6PM8cfDas","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see. The `---` line is a separator and `VARIATION: PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS` (ending with no colon at end) is a section header. \n\nNow let me understand why the compound title is being dropped. Looking at the dedup logic:\n1. Line 1: \"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS : PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS (VARIATION)\" - compound title\n2. Line 3: \"MAIN RECIPE: HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS\" - but this ends with `:` at the end? Wait... no it ends with \"MUSHROOMS\", not a colon. Let me check.\n\n\n3. The regex check `/:\\s*$/.test(text.trim())` only looks for a colon at the very end, so \"MAIN RECIPE: HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS\" passes through since it ends with \"MUSHROOMS\". Now I need to trace through the other filters to see what's actually blocking this line. I'm checking the regex logic more carefully—the filter at line 306 specifically looks for text that ends with a colon, not one that appears in the middle, so \"MAIN RECIPE: HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS\" would pass since it doesn't end with that character. The candidate has 7 words, which fits the requirement.\n\nNow I'm looking at what `isStructuralHeading` does—it identifies all-caps text with at least 2 words, and this title qualifies since every significant word has 4+ letters. The compound title with the parenthetical variation is interesting because the stripping logic preserves it when the content inside parentheses is all-caps.\n\nDuring deduplication, the longer compound title gets filtered out since it contains the shorter \"HERB ROASTED PORK WITH MUSHROOMS\" as a substring, so the shorter version survives. I need to trace through what happens with the \"VARIATION:\" prefix to see if there's another candidate being considered. I'm tracing through the logic to figure out where the `--` prefix is coming from. The line itself is \"VARIATION: PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS\" in the source, but it's appearing as `--VARIATION:` in the output, so something's prepending those dashes somewhere in the processing. So the `---` line by itself fails the hard filters because it's too short and looks garbled, but when joined with the variation text, it has enough letters to pass through and wouldn't trigger the garbled check.\n\nNow I'm checking whether the regex for bullet points actually matches `---` — the pattern looks for a single dash followed by whitespace, but `---` has three dashes in a row, so it might not match as expected. The vowel ratio checks out at 0.45, which is acceptable. Looking at the word-level checks now—the \"---\" prefix doesn't trigger the lowercase letter patterns, and there's no sentence boundary marker, so it passes the garbled text filter. Moving on to see if it matches the cooking instruction pattern with four or more words. The line passes all the hard filters, and it's in all caps with enough words and significant length, so it qualifies as a valid section header.\n\nBut I'm noticing the output shows `--VARIATION: PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS` instead of `--- VARIATION: PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS` — the dashes are different. Looking at the results file more carefully, I see this pattern repeated in other entries too, which suggests the `--` prefix might be coming from the input file itself or being added by the title-loop tool.\n\nWhen the `---` separator gets joined with the variation text, it should produce `--- VARIATION: PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS`, but then `normalizeOcrTitle` processes it. The function strips trailing section markers and applies substitutions to ALL_CAPS text, but I'm not sure it would change the `---` dashes themselves. Maybe the `--` is coming from `stripPageNumber` instead. I need to trace through the actual file structure more carefully—the `---` separator on line 32 and the `VARIATION:` text on line 34 are separated by an empty line, so they wouldn't be joined together in `mergedLines` since empty lines get filtered out during the build process.\n\nLooking at the actual output, the `--` prefix appears consistently across multiple results, which suggests it's coming from somewhere systematic rather than being a parsing artifact. Let me examine whether this prefix is being added by the CLI tool itself or if there's another source I'm missing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":340,"cache_read_input_tokens":86584,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":340},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ae7c1124-3c84-467a-af52-dc284b447f62","uuid":"71754036-e092-417f-8119-c17cc48bc44c"}
