{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019h5Y5aFoe1Dvd84Pefds1K","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `---` in the PIERNIK file is a separator. And the `WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ` is on line 31. Let me see what the full file looks like around those lines.\n\nOK, let me check the output again: for PIERNIK, the expected is `PIERNIK TRADYCYJNY + PIERNIK NOWOCZESNY Z CZEKOLADĄ` and the extracted is `--WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ`. The `--` prefix... maybe it comes from the `---` separator being joined with `WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ`? \n \nSo the `---` line gets filtered out as a candidate since it fails the garbled text check, but when lines are merged together, the `---` separator is still present in the merged output, which is why I'm seeing `---` concatenated with the next line.\n\nNow I need to check if this merged string passes the hard filters. The length is fine at 32 characters, and it doesn't look like metadata or start with a number. For the garbled check, I'm extracting just the letters: `WERSJANOWOCZESNAZCZEKOLADA` gives me 26 letters total, and I need to count the vowels to see if the ratio is reasonable. Checking whether the text matches a bullet point pattern—the regex requires a single dash followed by whitespace, but `---` has three consecutive dashes, so it doesn't trigger the bullet check. So filtering out single-letter words and those without enough alphabetic characters, I'm left with \"WERSJA\", \"NOWOCZESNA\", and \"CZEKOLADĄ\" — all of which have at least 4 letters. That's enough significant words to qualify as a structural heading.\n\nNow I'm realizing the full phrase \"WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ\" without the dashes would also pass the hard filters as a single-line candidate, so both versions could be in the running. But the actual output shows the dashes are included in the final result, which is interesting because...\n\nLet me trace through this differently. I need to look at what the title-loop evaluation tool is actually extracting and comparing against the expected values, and then check how the extract-title CLI is producing those results.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1174,"cache_read_input_tokens":91737,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1174},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ae7c1124-3c84-467a-af52-dc284b447f62","uuid":"f0447308-9df7-4367-b3da-c59583467154"}
