{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SfDzFkk9jKqTjhu8AQZhgf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to understand why the output shows `--WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ` rather than `--- WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ` or just `WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ`. Let me check the normalizeOcrTitle function more carefully. Actually, maybe `normalizeOcrTitle(\"--- WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ\")` strips the leading dashes in some way? No, it doesn't strip leading dashes.\n\nWait, maybe the `---` separator becomes `--` because `text.replace(/1/g, \"I\")` or other substitutions in normalizeOcrTitle change `---` somehow? But those only affect letters.\n\n\nLet me trace through normalizeOcrTitle step by step. First it strips trailing section markers, which doesn't apply here. Then it checks if the text is all caps using a function that extracts only letters—so for \"--- WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ\", it would check if \"WERSJANOWOCZESNAZCZEKOLAD\" is all uppercase, which it is.\n\nNext it applies character substitutions like replacing 1 with I, but none of these match the dashes or the Polish characters, so the text stays unchanged. Since nothing changed during substitution, it doesn't apply title-casing. So the result should be \"--- WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ\", but the actual output shows something different starting with \"--WERSJA NO\", which suggests something else is happening in the normalization process.\n\nLet me trace through the file structure more carefully. The grep output shows three dashes on line 29 for PIERNIK, but maybe the way lines are being joined or processed is collapsing or removing one of those dashes somehow. I need to look at exactly what's in the file and how `buildCandidates` is handling the line breaks.\n\nSo empty lines get skipped in the nonEmptyLines array, but the separator `---` itself has content so it gets included. When checking if it's all caps, the function looks for letters, finds none in `---`, so it doesn't get flagged as all-caps and just passes through unchanged. Now I'm trying to understand what happens during the mergedLines step and whether that's where the separator gets modified.\n\nLooking at the merge logic, the next line \"WERSJA\" doesn't start with any of the special characters that would trigger a merge, so these two lines stay separate. When I check if `---` passes the hard filters to become a candidate, it fails because it has fewer than 2 letters, making it look garbled. But when considering a 2-line join, the separator would combine with the following line to form `--- WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ`.\n\nNow checking if this joined version passes the filters—it does, since it has enough letters and looks legitimate. The blocking logic checks if `---` is a section label, but it's not in the section labels set, so the block doesn't apply. This means the 2-line join gets added as a valid candidate, though the output appears to be truncated.\n\nWait, I'm noticing something odd with the dashes. The output shows `--WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ` with only 2 dashes, but the input had 3 dashes plus a space. Let me trace through what's happening—when the text gets normalized and trimmed, something's shifting with how those dashes are being handled or merged.\n\nActually, I think I've been overanalyzing this. The real issue the improvement plan identifies is that lines starting with `--` (which mark sub-sections) shouldn't be joining with the next line at all. If I filter those out, this whole problem goes away. Let me just implement the planned changes systematically: first I'll create a food dictionary file for OCR corrections, then add a word repair function to handle common OCR mistakes.\n\nNow I'm looking at the rest of the implementation tasks—applying OCR repair before filtering, adjusting how position bonuses work for candidates, detecting when a page has no title and starts with ingredients instead, protecting compound titles from being deduplicated, filtering out metadata patterns like \"MAIN RECIPE:\", removing lines that start with `--`, and expanding the list of cooking verbs to recognize.\n\nI also need to handle bilingual layouts where a single word at the start is followed by a subtitle and ingredients, filter out garbled text that has pipes inserted between letters, and catch mixed Cyrillic and Latin characters that indicate corruption.\n\nThe tricky part is that protecting compound titles from dedup conflicts with the existing substring dedup logic—I need to find a way to exclude titles containing ` : ` or ` + ` from being removed without actually modifying the core dedup filter itself. I see the conflict now—the constraint forbids modifying the dedup block itself, but I need to protect compound titles from being deduplicated. Looking at the existing code, there are already several pre-dedup protections in place that remove problematic titles before the dedup logic even runs. So instead of trying to add a guard inside the filter, I should follow that same pattern and create a new pre-dedup protection specifically for compound titles with special characters. This way I'm adding protection before dedup rather than modifying dedup itself.\n\nWriting the protection logic... I need to add a filter to catch lines starting with two or more dashes, since they're visual separators creating spurious joins like \"--- VARIATION: PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS\". A simple regex check in `passesHardFilters` will handle these structural markers.\n\nNow I'm looking at the actual test results to see if this filter would help with cases like \"--BAKED COD WITH HERBS\" - these are getting marked as \"yes\" matches even though they shouldn't be. If I add the dash-prefix filter, the correct title would win out instead. I'm realizing the core problem: filtering lines that start with `--` would remove valid matches like `--BIGOS MYŚLIWSKI` that the evaluator currently accepts, but I need to filter out lines like `--- VARIATION: PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS` to fix Pattern 5. The challenge is distinguishing between two dashes (which should stay) and three or more dashes (which should be filtered). Looking for the generated test file for the Baked Cod case to see what output it's actually producing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3173,"cache_read_input_tokens":92911,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3173},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ae7c1124-3c84-467a-af52-dc284b447f62","uuid":"6841f8d9-64e3-4a32-b256-79509242ca2c"}
