{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NwyoCB4XVDpVhJS3u38wk3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so the file has `---` (3 dashes) on line 16, empty line 17, and `BAKED COD WITH HERBS` on line 18. The 2-line join would be `\"--- BAKED COD WITH HERBS\"` (after skipping empty lines). But the output shows `--BAKED COD WITH HERBS`.\n\nWait, maybe the `---` separator is actually TWO lines: line 16 is `---` and it's adjacent... but there's a blank line 17. So the 2-line join in buildCandidates would join `---` with `BAKED COD WITH HERBS` (skipping the blank).\n\n\nActually, I see now—buildCandidates filters out empty lines first, so the blank line gets skipped entirely, leaving `---` followed directly by `BAKED COD WITH HERBS` in the nonEmptyLines array.\n\nWhen joining them, I'd get `\"--- BAKED COD WITH HERBS\"` as a candidate. But that doesn't match the output `--BAKED COD WITH HERBS`, so there must be something else happening—maybe the hyphen-broken line merging logic is stripping or modifying the `---` before it even gets to the candidates loop. I see the issue now—the `---` separator is being caught by the hyphen-joining logic and merged with the next line, turning `---` plus `BAKED COD WITH HERBS` into a single candidate `--BAKED COD WITH HERBS`. Since this merged text is all uppercase and has enough words, it passes the structural heading check, which is why it's appearing in the output. So \"COD\" fails the four-letter requirement, meaning \"--BAKED COD WITH HERBS\" isn't actually a structural heading—it must just be scoring high enough to get selected anyway. For the PIERNIK TRADYCYJNY case, the triple dash on line 29 merges with the next line to create \"--WERSJA NOWOCZESNA Z CZEKOLADĄ\", and I'm checking what happens with HERB RO next.\n\nFor the ROASTED PORK variant, the triple dash on line 32 similarly merges with \"VARIATION: PORK WITH CARAMELIZED ONIONS\" to form \"--VARIATION: P